{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cc208f22-0e1a-45dd-8598-db9a8e2cb5b0","content":"The standard approach is to **abstract the file system behind an interface** and inject it:\n\n1. **Define an interface** like `IFileSystem` with methods matching what you use (`WriteAllText`, `ReadAllText`, `DirectoryExists`).\n2. **Create a real implementation** that delegates to `System.IO.File` / `Directory`.\n3. **Inject `IFileSystem`** into classes that need it via constructor injection.\n4. **In tests**, pass a mock/fake implementation.\n\nAlternatively, use the existing **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it provides `IFileSystem` and a `MockFileSystem` out of the box, saving you from writing your own.\n\n```csharp\n// With System.IO.Abstractions:\npublic class MyService\n{\n    private readonly IFileSystem _fs;\n    public MyService(IFileSystem fs) => _fs = fs;\n\n    public void Save(string path, string content)\n        => _fs.File.WriteAllText(path, content);\n}\n\n// In tests:\nvar fs = new MockFileSystem();\nvar svc = new MyService(fs);\nsvc.Save(\"/tmp/test.txt\", \"hello\");\nAssert.Equal(\"hello\", fs.File.ReadAllText(\"/tmp/test.txt\"));\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fbdf511b-5f97-4b06-898e-5494e45f25e1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in a .NET/C# project. This is a design/architecture question about testability patterns, not a code change request. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":369,"requestId":"0422:1C1C65:20F963B:2541474:69E8282B"},"id":"689e31bd-19b0-4536-a1a0-293c87c231dc","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:45:23.210Z","parentId":"b0a32a08-c7ba-49ee-81ee-92abfd608dac"}
